# introduction commands to see whats all about and the basic elements

Directory Structure
Linux uses a single root directory "/"
Everything (files & folders) starts from "/"
bash - /
COMMANDS ;

ls -- ðŸ“ƒ List Directory Contents 

ls-a -- List all files (including hidden)

ls-l -- List with details

more FILENAME -- more is the command to see a particular file ðŸ“„ View File Contents

cat FILENAME -- same as more an alternative command

mkdir directory_name -- make a new directive ðŸ“‚

mkdir dir1 dir2 dir3 -- for multiple directive making

mv file.txt folder/ -- mv is the command used to move 

mv oldname.txt newname.txt -- move also used as a rename command

cd folder_name -- to change directory to any particular directory that mentioned after the cd command

cd .. -- this command is used for going back one level (can be consider as a previos button of kind)

cd ~  -- this command is used to go back to home directory

pwd  -- this command is used for printing current location that you are in

cp  source destination -- cp command is basicaly copy and have to mention were is the copy content and were do you want to put it 

rm file.txt -- is used to remove or delete a file

rmdir folder_name -- for removing or deleting directory

rm -r folder_name -- for removing directory with files










